
JAZZ userware  - Information on hsp netlister
_______________________________________________________________

_______________________________________
Top level HSP netlister for import/synth blocks
_______________________________________

The HSP netlister allows reuse of previous design from other design systems.
The global hsp file is generated using information available from Composer's 
schematic sheets and from existing cbr/ckm/cdl files of blocks synthesized
using digital behavioral language (like Verilog) and/or hsp files generated 
by previously supported schematic capture tools (e.g. Logic Assist by Compass). 
To allow the assembly of these different blocks, a top-level schematic 
containing both regular schematic blocks and symbols pointing to hsp/ckm/cdl 
netlists has to be created in Composer. Such symbols must have the following
properties:

  synth_to_hsp=cbr	if the referenced cbr/cdl/ckm file has been synthesized from
			a Verilog description;
  import_to_hsp=hsp/hspnoedit	
			if the referenced hsp/ckm/cdl file comes from a LogicAssist 
			schematic capture. This property and the previous one
			are mutually exclusive;
  order=P1 P2 ... Pn	List of pins ordered according to the ".subckt" 
			statement of the top-level cell in the hsp/ckm netlist.
			This property is optional;


When specifying synth_to_hsp=ckm/import_to_hsp=hsp, the hsp netlister reads in the netlist
and substitutes the global nodes with local nodes (i.e. vdd>p, vss>n, vsub>sub),
which are then added to the ".subckt" I/O statement. Every Composer's symbol
is expected to have its supply, substrate and ground nodes defined as pins.

When specifying Import=hspnoedit/ckmnoedit/cdlnoedit, the hsp netlister reads in 
the netlist generated from Logic Assist. The netlist has already its power supply, 
substrate and ground nodes defined locally, hence the hsp netlist is not edited 
but just included in the top level hsp netlist. For the ckm/cdl netlists, there
are minor changes for model name, parameter unit, etc.

The netlist file locations are defined using the following environment variables:

setenv  RDS_COMPOSER_SYNTH	your_ckm_dir1:your_ckm_dir2:...
setenv  RDS_COMPOSER_IMPORT	your_hsp_dir1:your_hsp_dir2:...

_______________________________________
CDS mode and Compass mode
_______________________________________
CDS mode	allow the use of the Cadence model files for simulation.
Compass mode	allow the use of the Compass model files for simulation.

_______________________________________
Making the top level a "subcircuit"
_______________________________________
If you want to have the definition of the top level of the circuit enclosed within a ".subckt" definition line and a ".ends" termination
line, set the environment variable RDS_NL_COMMAND to "forcetopsub" before invoking Cadence tool:

setenv RDS_NL_COMMAND forcetopsub

_______________________________________
Long name mapping
_______________________________________
By default, HSP netlister maps all the node/instance names which are
longer than 16 characters.

You may turn off the name mapping by setting the environment variable RDS_COMPOSER_HSP_NAME_LENGTH to "off" 
before invoking Cadence tool:

setenv RDS_COMPOSER_HSP_NAME_LENGTH off

Or specify a longer name length upto 72:

setenv RDS_COMPOSER_HSP_NAME_LENGTH  60 
_______________________________________
hsp.ini file for configuration
_______________________________________

If ./hsp.ini file exists, use ./hsp.ini file. 
If no ./hsp.ini, but the file specified by environment variable RDS_CDS_HSP_INI exists, use the file.
Otherwise, no file is used for hsp netlist configuration at user level.

In the hsp.ini file, you may specify: 
1. [expandcount] : If you want to expand multi-instance devices to multiple lines, put "y" under [expandcount]. By default, you get one line with m=count.
2. [ignore] : A list of cells to be ignored.
3. [busformat] : If you want to use <> for busses, put "<" under [busformat]. if you want to use [] for busses, put "[" under [busformat].
4. [header] : header statements to be added to the beginning of the cell.hsp file to be generated.
5. [tailer] : tailer statements to be added to the end of the cell.hsp file to be generated. It replaces "${cellname}" with real cellname.
6. [noaif] : If you want to delete .aif file, put "y" under [noaif]. By default, you get .hsp file as well as .aif file.
7. [cfgfile] : If you want to create cell.cfg file, put "y" under [cfgfile].

Note: "#" at the beginning of lines is used as comment sign.

Example hsp.ini file:
=======================
[expandcount]
y
[noaif]
y
[ignore]
asheet
bsheet
[busformat]
<
[header]
.GLOBAL vss vdd
[tailer]
.include ${cellname}.hcf
.end
[cfgfile]
y
=======================
_______________________________________
The batch mode netlisters:
_______________________________________
usage: nlhsp cellname libname        #for HSPICE  (Compass)
usage: nlhspc cellname libname       #for HSPICE  (CDS)

Note: The nelisters need to be invoked from the directory in which you invoke Cadence system.
      libname can be ignored if your libname is ${PROJ_ID}_${LOGNAME}
      eg: ch25akit_test5 when login as test5 for ch25akit project.
      No Composer license is needed for using batch mode netlisters.

_______________________________________
output directory
_______________________________________
If environment variable HSP_DIR is set, the netlist is generated in the directory specified by HSP_DIR. Otherwise, the netlist is generated in the current directory.
 
